===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[criticize]] severely.
#* ''Matthew 11:20'',
#*: Then began he to '''upbraid''' the cities wherein most of his mighty works were done.
#* [[w:Philip Sidney|Sir Philip Sidney]] {{rfdatek|en|Sidney}},
#*: How much doth thy kindness '''upbraid''' my wickedness!
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To charge with something wrong or disgraceful; to [[reproach]]; to cast something in the teeth of; – followed by ''with'' or ''for'', and formerly ''of'', before the thing imputed.
#* {{rfdatek|en|Bible}} ''Mark 16:14'',
#*: And '''upbraided''' them with their unbelief.
#* {{rfdatek|en|Shakespeare}}
#*: Yet do not '''upbraid''' us our distress.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To treat with [[contempt]].
#* {{rfdatek|en|Spenser}}
#*:There also was that mighty monarch laid, Low under all, yet above all in pride; That name of native fire did foul '''upbraid''', And would, as Ammon's son, be magnify'd.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To object or urge as a matter of [[reproach]]; to cast up; – with ''to'' before the person.
#* {{rfdatek|en|Francis Bacon}}
#*:Those that have been bred together, are more apt to envy their equals when raised: for it doth '''upbraid''' unto them their own fortunes, and pointeth at them.
# {{lb|en|archaic|intransitive}} To utter upbraidings.
# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialectal|Northern England}} To rise on the stomach; [[vomit]]; [[retch]].

